The uppermost part of Egypt, marching with Ethiopia‚ is called the Thebaid. It is divided into prefectures of towns, called ‘ nomes '—the Ombite, Apollonopolite, Hermonthite, Thinite, Phaturite‚ Coptite, Tentyrite‚ Diospolite, Antaeopolite‚ Aphro- ditopolite and Lycopolite nomes. The nomes be- longing to the district in the neighbourhood of Pelu- sium are the Pharbaethite‚ Bubastite, Sethroite and Tanite. The remaining nomes are called the Arabie, Hammoniae (on the way to the oracle of Jupiter Ammon), Oxyrhynchste, Leontopolite, Athribite, Cynopolite‚ Hermopolite‚ Xoite, Mendesian‚ Seben- nyte, Cabasite, Latopolite, Heliopolite, Prosopste, Panopolite, Busirite, Onuphite‚ Saite, Ptenethus, Ptemphus, Naucratite, Metellite, Gynaecopolite‚ Menelaite-——these forming the region of Alexandria; and likeudse Mareotis belonging to Libya. The Heracleopolite nome is on an island of the Nile measuring 50 miles long, on which is also the town called the City of Hercules. There are two nomes called the Arsinoite3 these and the Memphite ex- tend to the apex of the Delta, adjacent to which on the side of Africa are the two Oasite nomes. Certain authorities alter some out of these names and substitute other nomes, for instance the Hero- polite and Crocodilopolite.
